# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aerodynamic
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] An **adjective** (abbreviated **ADJ**) is a word that describes or defines a noun or noun phrase.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Its semantic role is to change information given by the noun.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] The adjective is considered one of the main parts of speech of the English language, although historically they were classed together with nouns.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Nowadays, certain words that usually had been classified as adjectives, including *the*, *this*, *my*, etc., typically are classed separately, as determiners.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Depending on the language, an adjective can precede a corresponding noun on a prepositive basis or it can follow a corresponding noun on a postpositive basis.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Structural, contextual, and style considerations can impinge on the pre-or post-position of an adjective in a given instance of its occurrence.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Adjectives feature as a part of speech (word class) in most languages.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] In some languages, the words that serve the semantic function of adjectives are categorized together with some other class, such as nouns or verbs.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] In the phrase *a Ford car*, *Ford* is unquestionably a noun but its function is adjectival (noun adjunct, see below): to modify *car*.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] In some languages adjectives can function as nouns: for example, the Spanish phrase *un rojo* means 'a red [one]'.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] This is also possible in English, see above.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] As for "confusion" with verbs, rather than an adjective meaning "big", a language might have a verb that means "to be big" and could then use an attributive verb construction analogous to "big-being house" to express what in English is called a "big house".
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Such an analysis is possible for the grammar of Standard Chinese and Korean, for example.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Different languages do not use adjectives in exactly the same situations.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] For example, where English uses *"*to be *hungry*" (*hungry* being an adjective), Dutch, French, and Spanish use "*honger hebben*", "*avoir faim*", and "*tener hambre*" respectively (literally "to have hunger", the words for "hunger" being nouns).
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Similarly, where Hebrew uses the adjective זקוק‎ (*zaqūq*, roughly "in need of" or "needing"), English uses the verb "to need".
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] In languages that have adjectives as a word class, it is usually an open class; that is, it is relatively common for new adjectives to be formed via such processes as derivation.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] However, Bantu languages are well known for having only a small closed class of adjectives, and new adjectives are not easily derived.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Similarly, native Japanese adjectives (*i*-adjectives) are considered a closed class (as are native verbs), although nouns (an open class) may be used in the genitive to convey some adjectival meanings, and there is also the separate open class of adjectival nouns (*na*-adjectives).
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Many languages (including English) distinguish between adjectives, which qualify nouns and pronouns, and adverbs, which mainly modify verbs, adjectives, or other adverbs.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Not all languages make this exact distinction; many (including English) have words that can function as either.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] For example, in English, *fast* is an adjective in "a *fast* car" (where it qualifies the noun *car*) but an adverb in "he drove *fast*" (where it modifies the verb *drove*).
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] A German word like *klug* ("clever(ly)") takes endings when used as an attributive adjective but not when used adverbially.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Whether these are distinct parts of speech or distinct usages of the same part of speech is a question of analysis.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] While German linguistic terminology distinguishes *adverbiale* from *adjektivische Formen*, German refers to both as *Eigenschaftswörter* ("property words").
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Linguists today distinguish determiners from adjectives, considering them to be two separate parts of speech (or *lexical categories*).
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Determiners formerly were considered to be adjectives in some of their uses.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Determiners function neither as nouns nor pronouns but instead characterize a nominal element within a particular context.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] They generally do this by indicating definiteness (*a* vs.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] An adjective acts as the head of an *adjective phrase* or *adjectival phrase* (AP).
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] In the simplest case, an adjective phrase consists solely of the adjective; more complex adjective phrases may contain one or more adverbs modifying the adjective ("*very* strong"), or one or more complements (such as "worth *several dollars*", "full *of toys*", or "eager *to please*").
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] In English, attributive adjective phrases that include complements typically follow the noun that they qualify ("an evildoer *devoid of redeeming qualities*").
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] In many languages (including English) it is possible for nouns to modify other nouns.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Unlike adjectives, nouns acting as modifiers (called *attributive nouns* or *noun adjuncts*) usually are not predicative; a beautiful park is beautiful, but a car park is not "car".
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] The modifier often indicates origin ("*Virginia* reel"), purpose ("*work* clothes"), semantic patient ("*man* eater") or semantic subject ("*child* actor"); however, it may generally indicate almost any semantic relationship.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] It is also common for adjectives to be derived from nouns, as in *boyish*, *birdlike*, *behavioral (behavioural)*, *famous*, *manly*, *angelic*, and so on.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Many languages have participle forms that can act as noun modifiers either alone or as the head of a phrase.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Sometimes participles develop into functional usage as adjectives.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Examples in English include *relieved* (the past participle of *relieve*), used as an adjective in passive voice constructs such as "I am so *relieved* to see you".
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Other examples include *spoken* (the past participle of *speak*) and *going* (the present participle of *go*), which function as attribute adjectives in such phrases as "the *spoken* word" and "the *going* rate".
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Other constructs that often modify nouns include prepositional phrases (as in "a rebel *without a cause*"), relative clauses (as in "the man *who wasn't there*"), and infinitive phrases (as in "a cake *to die for*").
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Some nouns can also take complements such as content clauses (as in "the idea *that I would do that*"), but these are not commonly considered modifiers.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] For more information about possible modifiers and dependents of nouns, see Components of noun phrases.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] In Australian Aboriginal languages, the distinction between adjectives and nouns is typically thought weak, and many of the languages only use nouns, or nouns with a limited set of adjective-deriving affixes, to modify other nouns.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] In languages that have a subtle adjective-noun distinction, one way to tell them apart is that a modifying adjective can come to stand in for an entire elided noun phrase, while a modifying noun cannot.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] For example, in Bardi, the adjective *moorrooloo* 'little' in the phrase *moorrooloo* *baawa* 'little child' can stand on its own to mean 'the little one', while the attributive noun *aamba* 'man' in the phrase *aamba baawa* 'male child' cannot stand for the whole phrase to mean 'the male one'.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] In other languages, like Warlpiri, nouns and adjectives are lumped together beneath the nominal umbrella because of their shared syntactic distribution as arguments of predicates.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] The only thing distinguishing them is that some nominals seem to semantically denote entities (typically nouns in English) and some nominals seem to denote attributes (typically adjectives in English).
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] In many languages, attributive adjectives usually occur in a specific order.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] In general, the adjective order in English can be summarised as: opinion, size, age or shape, colour, origin, material, purpose.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Other language authorities, like the *Cambridge Dictionary*, state that shape precedes rather than follows age.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Determiners and postdeterminers—articles, numerals, and other limiters (e.g.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] *three* blind mice)—come before attributive adjectives in English.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Although certain combinations of determiners can appear before a noun, they are far more circumscribed than adjectives in their use—typically, only a single determiner would appear before a noun or noun phrase (including any attributive adjectives).
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Size – adjectives denoting physical size (e.g.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Shape or physical quality – adjectives describing more detailed physical attributes than overall size (e.g.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Colour – adjectives denoting colour or pattern (e.g.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Origin – denominal adjectives denoting source (e.g.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] This means that, in English, adjectives pertaining to size precede adjectives pertaining to age ("little old", not "old little"), which in turn generally precede adjectives pertaining to colour ("old white", not "white old").
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] This order may be more rigid in some languages than others; in some, like Spanish, it may only be a default (*unmarked*) word order, with other orders being permissible.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Other languages, such as Tagalog, follow their adjectival orders as rigidly as English.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] The normal adjectival order of English may be overridden in certain circumstances, especially when one adjective is being fronted or with ablaut reduplication.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] For example, the usual order of adjectives in English would result in the phrase "the bad big wolf" (opinion before size), but instead, the usual phrase is "the big bad wolf".
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Owing partially to borrowings from French, English has some adjectives that follow the noun as postmodifiers, called postpositive adjectives, as in *time immemorial* and *attorney general*.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Adjectives may even change meaning depending on whether they precede or follow, as in *proper*: "They live in a *proper town*" (a real town, not a village) vs.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] "They live in the *town proper* (in the town itself, not in the suburbs).
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] In many languages, some adjectives are *comparable* and the measure of comparison is called *degree*.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] For example, a person may be "polite", but another person may be "*more* polite", and a third person may be the "*most* polite" of the three.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] The word "more" here modifies the adjective "polite" to indicate a comparison is being made, and "most" modifies the adjective to indicate an absolute comparison (a *superlative*).
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Among languages that allow adjectives to be compared, different means are used to indicate comparison.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Some languages do not distinguish between comparative and superlative forms.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Other languages allow adjectives to be compared but do not have a special comparative form of the adjective.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] In such cases, as in some Australian Aboriginal languages, case-marking, such as the ablative case, may be used to indicate one entity has more of an adjectival quality than (i.e.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Another way to convey comparison is by incorporating the words "more" and "most".
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] There is no simple rule to decide which means is correct for any given adjective, however.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] The general tendency is for simpler adjectives and those from Anglo-Saxon to take the suffixes, while longer adjectives and those from French, Latin, or Greek do not—but sometimes the *sound* of the word is the deciding factor.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Many adjectives do not naturally lend themselves to comparison.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] For example, some English speakers would argue that it does not make sense to say that one thing is "more ultimate" than another, or that something is "most ultimate", since the word "ultimate" is already absolute in its semantics.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Such adjectives are called *non-comparable* or *absolute*.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Nevertheless, native speakers will frequently play with the raised forms of adjectives of this sort.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Although "pregnant" is logically non-comparable (either one is pregnant or not), one may hear a sentence like "She looks more and more pregnant each day".
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Comparative and superlative forms are also occasionally used for other purposes than comparison.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] In Italian, superlatives are frequently used to put strong emphasis on an adjective: *bellissimo* means "most beautiful", but is in fact more commonly heard in the sense "extremely beautiful".
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Attributive adjectives and other noun modifiers may be used either *restrictively* (helping to identify the noun's referent, hence "restricting" its reference) or *non-restrictively* (helping to describe a noun).
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Here "difficult" is restrictive – it tells which tasks he avoids, distinguishing these from the easy ones: "Only those tasks that are difficult".
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] In English, restrictiveness is not marked on adjectives but is marked on relative clauses (the difference between "the man *who recognized me* was there" and "the man, *who recognized me*, was there" being one of restrictiveness).
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] In some languages, adjectives alter their form to reflect the gender, case and number of the noun that they describe.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Here, a distinction may be made between attributive and predicative usage.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] In English, adjectives never agree, whereas in French, they always agree.
[src:aerodynamic/adjective] Semanticist Barbara Partee classifies adjectives semantically as intersective, subsective, or nonsubsective, with nonsubsective adjectives being plain nonsubsective or privative.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Modern aerodynamics only dates back to the seventeenth century, but aerodynamic forces have been harnessed by humans for thousands of years in sailboats and windmills, and images and stories of flight appear throughout recorded history including the Ancient Greek legend of Icarus and Daedalus.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Fundamental concepts of continuum, drag, and pressure gradients appear in the work of Aristotle and Archimedes.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] In 1726, Sir Isaac Newton became the first person to develop a theory of air resistance, making him one of the first aerodynamicists.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Dutch-Swiss mathematician Daniel Bernoulli followed in 1738 with *Hydrodynamica* in which he described a fundamental relationship between pressure, density, and flow velocity for incompressible flow known today as Bernoulli's principle, which provides one method for calculating aerodynamic lift.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] In 1757, Leonhard Euler published the more general Euler equations which could be applied to both compressible and incompressible flows.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] The Euler equations were extended to incorporate the effects of viscosity in the first half of the 1800s, resulting in the Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] The Navier–Stokes equations are the most general governing equations of fluid flow but are difficult to solve for the flow around all but the simplest of shapes.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] In 1799, Sir George Cayley became the first person to identify the four aerodynamic forces of flight (weight, lift, drag, and thrust), as well as the relationships between them, and in doing so outlined the path toward achieving heavier-than-air flight for the next century.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] In 1871, Francis Herbert Wenham constructed the first wind tunnel, allowing precise measurements of aerodynamic forces.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Drag theories were developed by Jean Le Rond d'Alembert, Gustav Kirchhoff, and Lord Rayleigh.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] In 1889, Charles Renard, a French aeronautical engineer, became the first person to reasonably predict the power needed for sustained flight.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Otto Lilienthal, the first person to become highly successful with glider flights, was also the first to propose thin, curved airfoils that would produce high lift and low drag.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Building on these developments as well as research carried out in their own wind tunnel, the Wright brothers flew the first powered airplane on December 17, 1903.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] During the time of the first flights, Frederick W.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Lanchester, Martin Kutta, and Nikolai Zhukovsky independently created theories which connected circulation of a fluid flow to lift.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Kutta and Zhukovsky then developed a two-dimensional wing theory.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Expanding upon the work of Lanchester, Ludwig Prandtl is credited with developing the mathematics behind thin-airfoil and lifting-line theories as well as working with boundary layers.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] As aircraft speed increased designers began to encounter challenges associated with air compressibility at speeds near the speed of sound.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] The differences in airflow under such conditions lead to problems in aircraft control, increased drag due to shock waves and the threat of structural failure due to aeroelastic flutter.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] The ratio of the flow speed to the speed of sound was named the Mach number after Ernst Mach who was one of the first to investigate the properties of the supersonic flow.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Macquorn Rankine and Pierre Henri Hugoniot independently developed the theory for flow properties before and after a shock wave, while Jakob Ackeret led the initial work of calculating the lift and drag of supersonic airfoils.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Theodore von Kármán and Hugh Latimer Dryden introduced the term transonic to describe flow speeds between the critical Mach number and Mach 1 where drag increases rapidly.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] The rapid increase in drag led aerodynamicists and aviators to disagree on whether supersonic flight was achievable until the sound barrier was broken in 1947 using the Bell X-1 aircraft.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] By the time the sound barrier was broken, aerodynamicists' understanding of the subsonic and low supersonic flow had matured.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] The Cold War prompted the design of an ever-evolving line of high-performance aircraft.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Computational fluid dynamics began as an effort to solve for flow properties around complex objects and has rapidly grown to the point where entire aircraft can be designed using computer software, with wind-tunnel tests followed by flight tests to confirm the computer predictions.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Understanding of supersonic and hypersonic aerodynamics has matured since the 1960s, and the goals of aerodynamicists have shifted from the behaviour of fluid flow to the engineering of a vehicle such that it interacts predictably with the fluid flow.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Understanding the motion of air around an object (often called a flow field) enables the calculation of forces and moments acting on the object.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] In many aerodynamics problems, the forces of interest are the fundamental forces of flight: lift, drag, thrust, and weight.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Of these, lift and drag are aerodynamic forces, i.e. forces due to air flow over a solid body.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Calculation of these quantities is often founded upon the assumption that the flow field behaves as a continuum.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Continuum flow fields are characterized by properties such as flow velocity, pressure, density, and temperature, which may be functions of position and time.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] These properties may be directly or indirectly measured in aerodynamics experiments or calculated starting with the equations for conservation of mass, momentum, and energy in air flows.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Density, flow velocity, and an additional property, viscosity, are used to classify flow fields.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Flow velocity is used to classify flows according to speed regime.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Subsonic flows are flow fields in which the air speed field is always below the local speed of sound.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Transonic flows include both regions of subsonic flow and regions in which the local flow speed is greater than the local speed of sound.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Supersonic flows are defined to be flows in which the flow speed is greater than the speed of sound everywhere.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] A fourth classification, hypersonic flow, refers to flows where the flow speed is much greater than the speed of sound.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Aerodynamicists disagree on the precise definition of hypersonic flow.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Compressible flow accounts for varying density within the flow.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Subsonic flows are often idealized as incompressible, i.e. the density is assumed to be constant.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Transonic and supersonic flows are compressible, and calculations that neglect the changes of density in these flow fields will yield inaccurate results.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Viscosity is associated with the frictional forces in a flow.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] In some flow fields, viscous effects are very small, and approximate solutions may safely neglect viscous effects.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] These approximations are called inviscid flows.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Flows for which viscosity is not neglected are called viscous flows.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Finally, aerodynamic problems may also be classified by the flow environment.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] External aerodynamics is the study of flow around solid objects of various shapes (e.g. around an airplane wing), while internal aerodynamics is the study of flow through passages inside solid objects (e.g. through a jet engine).
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Unlike liquids and solids, gases are composed of discrete molecules which occupy only a small fraction of the volume filled by the gas.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] On a molecular level, flow fields are made up of the collisions of many individual gas molecules among themselves, and their collisions with solid surfaces.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] However, in most aerodynamics applications, the discrete molecular nature of gases is ignored, and the flow field is assumed to behave as a continuum.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] This assumption allows fluid properties such as density and flow velocity to be defined everywhere within the flow.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] The validity of the continuum assumption is dependent on the density of the gas and the application in question.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] For the continuum assumption to be valid, the mean free path length must be much smaller than the length scale of the application in question.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] For example, many aerodynamics applications deal with aircraft flying in atmospheric conditions, where the mean free path length is on the order of micrometers and where the body is orders of magnitude larger.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] In these cases, the length scale of the aircraft ranges from a few meters to a few tens of meters, which is much larger than the mean free path length.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] For such applications, the continuum assumption is reasonable.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] The continuum assumption is less valid for extremely low-density flows like those encountered by vehicles at very high altitudes (e.g.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] 300,000 ft/90 km) or satellites in Low Earth orbit.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] In these cases, statistical mechanics is a more accurate method of solving the problem than is continuum aerodynamics.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] The Knudsen number can be used to guide the choice between statistical mechanics and the continuous formulation of aerodynamics.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] The assumption of a fluid continuum allows problems in aerodynamics to be solved using fluid dynamics conservation laws.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Together, the equations are known as Navier–Stokes equations, although some authors define the term to only include the momentum equation(s).
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Navier–Stokes equations have no known analytical solution and are solved in modern aerodynamics using computational techniques.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Because computational methods using high speed computers were not historically available and the high computational cost of solving these complex equations now that they are available, simplifications of the Navier–Stokes equations have been and continue to be employed.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Euler equations are a set of similar conservation equations which neglect viscosity and may be used in cases where the effect of viscosity is expected to be small.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Further simplifications lead to Laplace's equation and potential flow theory.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Additionally, Bernoulli's equation is a solution in one dimension to both the momentum and energy conservation equations.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] The ideal gas law or another such equation of state is often used in conjunction with these equations to form a determined system which allows the solution for the unknown variables.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Aerodynamic problems are classified by the flow environment or properties of the flow, including flow speed, compressibility, and viscosity.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] *External* aerodynamics is the study of flow around solid objects of various shapes.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Evaluating the lift and drag on an airplane or the shock waves that form in front of the nose of a rocket are examples of external aerodynamics.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] *Internal* aerodynamics is the study of flow through passages in solid objects.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] For instance, internal aerodynamics encompasses the study of the airflow through a jet engine or through an air conditioning pipe.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Aerodynamic problems can also be classified according to whether the flow speed is below, near or above the speed of sound.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Aerodynamicists disagree over the precise definition of hypersonic flow; a rough definition considers flows with Mach numbers above 5 to be hypersonic.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] The influence of viscosity on the flow dictates a third classification.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Some problems may encounter only very small viscous effects, in that case viscosity can be considered to be negligible.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] The approximations to these problems are called inviscid flows.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Flows for which viscosity cannot be neglected are called viscous flows.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] An incompressible flow is a flow in which density is constant in both time and space.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Although all real fluids are compressible, a flow is often approximated as incompressible if the effect of the density changes cause only small changes to the calculated results.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] This is more likely to be true when the flow speeds are significantly lower than the speed of sound.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Effects of compressibility are more significant at speeds close to or above the speed of sound.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] The Mach number is used to evaluate whether the incompressibility can be assumed, otherwise the effects of compressibility must be included.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Subsonic (or low-speed) aerodynamics describes fluid motion in flows which are much lower than the speed of sound everywhere in the flow.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] There are several branches of subsonic flow but one special case arises when the flow is inviscid, incompressible and irrotational.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] This case is called potential flow and allows the differential equations which describe the flow to be a simplified version of the equations of fluid dynamics, thus making available to the aerodynamicist a range of quick and easy solutions.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] In solving a subsonic problem, one decision to be made by the aerodynamicist is whether to incorporate the effects of compressibility.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Compressibility is a description of the amount of change of density in the flow.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] When the effects of compressibility on the solution are small, the assumption that density is constant may be made.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] The problem is then an incompressible low-speed aerodynamics problem.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] When the density is allowed to vary, the flow is called compressible.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] In air, compressibility effects are usually ignored when the Mach number in the flow does not exceed 0.3 (about 335 feet (102 m) per second or 228 miles (366 km) per hour at 60 °F (16 °C)).
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Above Mach 0.3, the problem flow should be described using compressible aerodynamics.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] According to the theory of aerodynamics, a flow is considered to be compressible if the density changes along a streamline.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] This means that–unlike incompressible flow–changes in density are considered.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] In general, this is the case where the Mach number in part or all of the flow exceeds 0.3.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] The Mach 0.3 value is rather arbitrary, but it is used because gas flows with a Mach number below that value demonstrate changes in density of less than 5%.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Furthermore, that maximum 5% density change occurs at the stagnation point (the point on the object where flow speed is zero), while the density changes around the rest of the object will be significantly lower.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Transonic, supersonic, and hypersonic flows are all compressible flows.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] The term Transonic refers to a range of flow velocities just below and above the local speed of sound (generally taken as Mach 0.8–1.2).
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] It is defined as the range of speeds between the critical Mach number, when some parts of the airflow over an aircraft become supersonic, and a higher speed, typically near Mach 1.2, when all of the airflow is supersonic.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Between these speeds, some of the airflow is supersonic, while some of the airflow is not supersonic.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Supersonic aerodynamic problems are those involving flow speeds greater than the speed of sound.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Calculating the lift on the Concorde during cruise can be an example of a supersonic aerodynamic problem.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Supersonic flow behaves very differently from subsonic flow.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Fluids react to differences in pressure; pressure changes are how a fluid is "told" to respond to its environment.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Therefore, since sound is in fact, an infinitesimal pressure difference propagating through a fluid, the speed of sound in that fluid can be considered the fastest speed that "information" can travel in the flow.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] This difference most obviously manifests itself in the case of a fluid striking an object.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] In front of that object, the fluid builds up a stagnation pressure as impact with the object brings the moving fluid to rest.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] In fluid traveling at subsonic speed, this pressure disturbance can propagate upstream, changing the flow pattern ahead of the object and giving the impression that the fluid "knows" the object is there by seemingly adjusting its movement and is flowing around it.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] In a supersonic flow, however, the pressure disturbance cannot propagate upstream.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Thus, when the fluid finally reaches the object it strikes it and the fluid is forced to change its properties – temperature, density, pressure, and Mach number—in an extremely violent and irreversible fashion called a shock wave.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] The presence of shock waves, along with the compressibility effects of high-flow velocity (see Reynolds number) fluids, is the central difference between the supersonic and subsonic aerodynamics regimes.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] In aerodynamics, hypersonic speeds are speeds that are highly supersonic.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] In the 1970s, the term generally came to refer to speeds of Mach 5 (5 times the speed of sound) and above.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] The hypersonic regime is a subset of the supersonic regime.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Hypersonic flow is characterized by high temperature flow behind a shock wave, viscous interaction, and chemical dissociation of gas.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] The incompressible and compressible flow regimes produce many associated phenomena, such as boundary layers and turbulence.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] The concept of a boundary layer is important in many problems in aerodynamics.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] The viscosity and fluid friction in the air is approximated as being significant only in this thin layer.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] This assumption makes the description of such aerodynamics much more tractable mathematically.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] In aerodynamics, turbulence is characterized by chaotic property changes in the flow.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] These include low momentum diffusion, high momentum convection, and rapid variation of pressure and flow velocity in space and time.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Flow that is not turbulent is called laminar flow.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Aerodynamics is a significant element of vehicle design, including road cars and trucks where the main goal is to reduce the vehicle drag coefficient, and racing cars, where in addition to reducing drag the goal is also to increase the overall level of downforce.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Aerodynamics is also important in the prediction of forces and moments acting on sailing vessels.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] It is used in the design of mechanical components such as hard drive heads.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Structural engineers resort to aerodynamics, and particularly aeroelasticity, when calculating wind loads in the design of large buildings, bridges, and wind turbines.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] The aerodynamics of internal passages is important in heating/ventilation, gas piping, and in automotive engines where detailed flow patterns strongly affect the performance of the engine.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Urban aerodynamics are studied by town planners and designers seeking to improve amenity in outdoor spaces, or in creating urban microclimates to reduce the effects of urban pollution.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] The field of environmental aerodynamics describes ways in which atmospheric circulation and flight mechanics affect ecosystems.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Aerodynamic equations are used in numerical weather prediction.
[src:aerodynamic/aerodynamic] Sports in which aerodynamics are of crucial importance include soccer, table tennis, cricket, baseball, and golf, in which most players can control the trajectory of the ball using the "Magnus effect".
[src:aerodynamic/noun] In grammar, a **noun** is a word that represents a concrete or abstract thing, like living creatures, places, actions, events, qualities, states of existence, and ideas.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] To summarize this, nouns signify an object or idea.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] A noun may serve as an object or subject within a phrase, clause, or sentence.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] In linguistics, nouns constitute a lexical category (part of speech) defined according to how its members combine with members of other lexical categories.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] The syntactic occurrence of nouns differs among languages.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] In English, prototypical nouns are common nouns or proper nouns that can occur with determiners, articles and attributive adjectives, and can function as the head of a noun phrase.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] According to traditional and popular classification, pronouns are distinct from nouns, but in much modern theory they are considered a subclass of nouns.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] Every language has various linguistic and grammatical distinctions between nouns and verbs.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] Word classes (parts of speech) were described by Sanskrit grammarians from at least the 5th century BC.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] In Yāska's *Nirukta*, the noun (*nāma*) is one of the four main categories of words defined.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] The Ancient Greek equivalent was *ónoma* (ὄνομα), referred to by Plato in the *Cratylus*, and later listed as one of the eight parts of speech in *The Art of Grammar*, attributed to Dionysius Thrax (2nd century BC).
[src:aerodynamic/noun] The term used in Latin grammar was *nōmen*.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] All of these terms for "noun" were also words meaning "name".
[src:aerodynamic/noun] The English word *noun* is derived from the Latin term, through the Anglo-Norman *nom* (other forms include *nomme*, and *noun* itself).
[src:aerodynamic/noun] The word classes were defined partly by the grammatical forms that they take.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] In Sanskrit, Greek, and Latin, for example, nouns are categorized by gender and inflected for case and number.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] Because adjectives share these three grammatical categories, adjectives typically were placed in the same class as nouns.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] Similarly, the Latin term *nōmen* includes both nouns (substantives) and adjectives, as originally did the English word *noun*, the two types being distinguished as *nouns substantive* and *nouns adjective* (or *substantive nouns* and *adjective nouns*, or simply *substantives* and *adjectives*).
[src:aerodynamic/noun] Many European languages use a cognate of the word *substantive* as the basic term for *noun* (for example, Spanish *sustantivo*, "noun").
[src:aerodynamic/noun] Nouns in the dictionaries of such languages are demarked by the abbreviation *s.* or *sb.* instead of *n.*, which may be used for proper nouns or neuter nouns instead.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] In English, some modern authors use the word *substantive* to refer to a class that includes both nouns (single words) and noun phrases (multiword units that are sometimes called *noun equivalents*).
[src:aerodynamic/noun] It can also be used as a counterpart to *attributive* when distinguishing between a noun being used as the head (main word) of a noun phrase and a noun being used as a noun adjunct.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] For example, the noun *knee* can be said to be used substantively in *my knee hurts*, but attributively in *the patient needed knee replacement*.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] A noun can co-occur with an article or an attributive adjective.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] In the following, an asterisk (*) in front of an example means that this example is ungrammatical.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] Nouns have sometimes been characterized in terms of the grammatical categories by which they may be varied (for example gender, case, and number).
[src:aerodynamic/noun] Such definitions tend to be language-specific, since different languages may apply different categories.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] Nouns are frequently defined, particularly in informal contexts, in terms of their semantic properties (their meanings).
[src:aerodynamic/noun] Nouns are described as words that refer to a *person*, *place*, *thing*, *event*, *substance*, *quality*, *quantity*, etc., but this manner of definition has been criticized as uninformative.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] Several English nouns lack an intrinsic referent of their own: *behalf* (as in *on behalf of*), *dint* (*by dint of*), and *sake* (*for the sake of*).
[src:aerodynamic/noun] Moreover, other parts of speech may have reference-like properties: the verbs *to rain* or *to mother*, or adjectives like *red*; and there is little difference between the adverb *gleefully* and the prepositional phrase *with glee*.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] A functional approach defines a noun as a word that can be the head of a nominal phrase, i.e., a phrase with referential function, without needing to go through morphological transformation.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] Nouns can have a number of different properties and are often sub-categorized based on various of these criteria, depending on their occurrence in a language.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] Nouns may be classified according to morphological properties such as which prefixes or suffixes they take, and also their relations in syntax – how they combine with other words and expressions of various types.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] Many such classifications are language-specific, given the obvious differences in syntax and morphology.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] In English for example, it might be noted that nouns are words that can co-occur with definite articles (as stated at the start of this article), but this could not apply in Russian, which has no definite articles.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] In some languages common and proper nouns have grammatical gender, typically masculine, feminine, and neuter.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] The gender of a noun (as well as its number and case, where applicable) will often require agreement in words that modify or are used along with it.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] In French for example, the singular form of the definite article is *le* for masculine nouns and *la* for feminine; adjectives and certain verb forms also change (sometimes with the simple addition of *-e* for feminine).
[src:aerodynamic/noun] Grammatical gender often correlates with the form of the noun and the inflection pattern it follows; for example, in both Italian and Romanian most nouns ending in *-a* are feminine.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] Gender can also correlate with the sex or social gender of the noun's referent, particularly in the case of nouns denoting people (and sometimes animals), though with exceptions (the feminine French noun *personne* can refer to a male or a female person).
[src:aerodynamic/noun] In Modern English, even common nouns like *hen* and *princess* and proper nouns like *Alicia* do not have grammatical gender (their femininity has no relevance in syntax), though they denote persons or animals of a specific sex.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] The gender of a pronoun must be appropriate for the item referred to: "The *girl* said the *ring* was from *her* new *boyfriend*, but *he* denied *it* was from *him*" (three nouns; and three gendered pronouns: or four, if this *her* is counted as a possessive pronoun).
[src:aerodynamic/noun] Many nouns have both countable and uncountable uses; for example, *soda* is countable in "give me three sodas", but uncountable in "he likes soda".
[src:aerodynamic/noun] Some nouns have both concrete and abstract meanings: *art* usually refers to something abstract ("Art is important in human culture"), but it can also refer to a concrete item ("I put my daughter's art up on the fridge").
[src:aerodynamic/noun] A noun might have a literal (concrete) and also a figurative (abstract) meaning: "a brass *key*" and "the *key* to success"; "a *block* in the pipe" and "a mental *block*".
[src:aerodynamic/noun] Similarly, some abstract nouns have developed etymologically by figurative extension from literal roots (*drawback*, *fraction*, *holdout*, *uptake*).
[src:aerodynamic/noun] Many abstract nouns in English are formed by adding a suffix (*-ness*, *-ity*, *-ion*) to adjectives or verbs (*happiness* and *serenity* from the adjectives *happy* and *serene*; *circulation* from the verb *circulate*).
[src:aerodynamic/noun] Illustrating the wide range of possible classifying principles for nouns, the Awa language of Papua New Guinea regiments nouns according to how *ownership* is assigned: as alienable possession or inalienable possession.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] An alienably possessed item (a tree, for example) can exist even without a possessor.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] But inalienably possessed items are necessarily associated with their possessor and are referred to differently, for example with nouns that function as kin terms (meaning "father", etc.), body-part nouns (meaning "shadow", "hair", etc.), or part–whole nouns (meaning "top", "bottom", etc.).
[src:aerodynamic/noun] A noun phrase (or **NP**) is a phrase usually headed by a common noun, a proper noun, or a pronoun.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] The head may be the only constituent, or it may be modified by determiners and adjectives.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] For example, "The dog sat near Ms Curtis and wagged its tail" contains three NPs: *the dog* (subject of the verbs *sat* and *wagged*); *Ms Curtis* (complement of the preposition *near*); and *its tail* (object of *wagged*).
[src:aerodynamic/noun] "You became their teacher" contains two NPs: *you* (subject of *became*); and *their teacher*.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] For example, in the sentence "Gareth thought she was weird", the word *she* is a pronoun that refers to a person just as the noun *Gareth* does.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] The word *one* can replace parts of noun phrases, and it sometimes stands in for a noun.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] But *one* can also stand in for larger parts of a noun phrase.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] For example, in the following example, *one* can stand in for *new car*.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] Nominalization is a process whereby a word that belongs to another part of speech comes to be used as a noun.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] This can be a way to create new nouns, or to use other words in ways that resemble nouns.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] In French and Spanish, for example, adjectives frequently act as nouns referring to people who have the characteristics denoted by the adjective.
[src:aerodynamic/noun] is a worldwide association of political parties.
